# DOM Height Changes — add y-overflow compensation

When implementing any system that adds/removes/hides/shows DOM elements (modals, accordions, lists, dynamic rows, banners, toolbars), include basic vertical overflow compensation in the same change.

## Minimum required behavior

1. Identify the intended scroll container (`body`, panel body, list region, modal body, etc.).
2. Keep container height bounded (`max-height`/fixed clamp), and enable inner scrolling (`overflow-y: auto` or `scroll`) when content can grow.
3. Prevent layout jump when possible (stable region height, padding for scrollbar gutter, or equivalent guard).
4. If only a subsection should scroll, scope overflow to that subsection instead of the entire modal/page.

## Default implementation hints

- Prefer `min-height: 0` on grid/flex children that need to scroll.
- For modal/panel content, use `grid-template-rows: auto minmax(0, 1fr)` and set overflow on the second row.
- For dynamic lists, cap height and scroll inside the list region.

## Quick examples

```css
.panelBody {
  min-height: 0;
  max-height: min(70vh, 640px);
  overflow-y: auto;
}
```

```css
.modal {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-rows: auto minmax(0, 1fr);
}
.modalContent {
  min-height: 0;
  overflow-y: auto;
}
```
